  {
    "id": "1837160754732019743",
    "text": "Beneath all his sophistry, one thing becomes unmistakably clear: he harbors a deep resentment toward women, likely rooted in his troubled relationship with his mother.\n\nIn “Hillbilly Elegy”, J.D. Vance recounts his mother’s battles with addiction and instability, which cast a shadow over his childhood and shaped his worldview.\n\nChildhood trauma often plays a pivotal role in the negative narratives we create about ourselves and others. Yet, unlike most, Vance could potentially be just a heartbeat away from the presidency. \n\nUnprocessed trauma can become a corrosive force, poisoning the soul and shaping one's actions in ways that affect not just the individual, but an entire nation.",
    "author": {
      "id": "4018888580",
      "name": "The Intellectualist",
      "screenName": "highbrow_nobrow",
      "profileImageUrl": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/658451233057804291/4R_pmaso_normal.png",
      "verified": true
    },
